k presents a collection of Galen’s enduring insights about how we can take care of our bodies and minds, prevent disease, and reach a healthy old age.Although we now know that many of Galen’s ideas about physiology are wrong, How to Be Healthy shows that much of his advice remains sound. In these selections from his writings, presented in fresh translations, Galen discusses the art of medicine, exercise and diet, the mind-body connection, the difficulty of applying general medical principles to individuals, and much more. Featuring an introduction, brief commentaries that connect ancient medical practices to modern ones, and the original Greek on facing pages, How to Be Healthy offers an entertaining and enlightening new perspective on the age-old pursuit of wellness, from the importance of “the exercise with a small ball” to the benefits of “avoiding distress.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMedicine, Greek and RomanvEarly works to 1800. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAncient History.  aAncient Rome.  aAncient World.  aAncient wisdom.  aGalen.  aKatherine D. Van Schaik.  aPrinceton University Press.  aWisdom series.  aancient Greek.  aancient guides.  aancient philosophy.  agift book.  ahealth.  ahow to be healthy.  amindfulness.  aphilosopher.  aphilosophy.  awellness.1 aVan Schaik, Katherine D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074975540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691242897?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691242897423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691242897/original  a978-3-11-074975-5  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2